provenance.section_title: The Criteria: What We Look for in a Great Set of Poultry Shears
provenance.paragraph_text: A good pair of poultry shears should do two things well: It needs to cleanly snip through slippery skin, and it needs to force its way through bone. That sounds simple enough, but it's probably pretty hard to pack both capabilities into one set of shears, as bone-crushing power and skin-snipping finesse are very different things. The fact that so many manufacturers seem to have such a hard time ensuring that their shears can do both likely speaks to the overall technical challenge. And yet, that's what poultry shears need to do if they're going to be worth buying and using.

why does the duck skin need to be pricked?

Duck is high in fat, so when roasting a whole duck you can end up with a lot of fat left with the duck inside the skin and soggier skin. This can present a challenge when cooking, because we want the fat to render out and the skin to become crispy and delicious.The most common way to do this, classically, is to prick the skin all over, to permit the fat an exit path (when doing this, be careful to cut through the skin into the fat layer, but hopefully not into the meat itself)

provenance.page_title: How do I roast a whole duck so that fat drips out easily and the skin gets crispy?
provenance.paragraph_text: Among poultry, duck is exceptionally fatty, and a lot of its fat is directly underneath the skin.  This can present a challenge when cooking, because we want the fat to render out and the skin to become crispy and delicious.The most common way to do this, classically, is to:Dock (or less commonly, score) the skin all over, to permit the fat an exit path (when doing this, be careful to cut through the skin into the fat layer, but hopefully not into the meat itself)Roast at a relatively low temperature for to permit the fat time to melt and drip away; many recipes then finish on a higher temperature for crisping and browningLike all poultry, salting the duck a day ahead, and then letting it sit in the refrigerator will also promote crispiness, but it is far less of a factor with duck which cooks and renders for a longer period of time.

conversation.utterance: what is the origin of this recipe?

Duck à l'orange, or canard à l'orange in French, is a classic French dish in which a duck is roasted and served with a bigarade sauce. The Italians claim it migrated from Italy to France. Italian poet Antonio Caccitore detailed his first encounter with duck à l'orange outside of Italy in the poem "Anatra all'Arancia", which tells the story of how the dish made its way to Paris from its origin in Naples.
